# Project Architecture

This file describes the target structure of the workspace. It is a reference architecture, not a requirement that every file already exists.

```text
books/
  _template/
    rules/
      project.mdc
      style.mdc

  <project_id>/
    rules/
      project.mdc
      style.mdc

    # standalone mode: one project equals one book
    outline.md
    characters.md
    world-rules.md              # optional
    timeline.md                 # optional
    chapters/
      ch01.md
    plans/
      ch01_plan.md
    critique/
      ch01_critique.md
    revisions/
      ch01_revision.md
    memory/
      events.md
      relationships.md
      foreshadowing.md
      mistakes.md

    # series mode: one project equals one series
    outline.md                  # series arc
    characters.md               # long-range character canon
    world-rules.md              # optional
    timeline.md                 # series timeline
    memory/
      events.md                 # series-level canon only
      relationships.md
      foreshadowing.md
      unresolved-threads.md
      book-status.md
      mistakes.md
    volumes/
      book01/
        outline.md
        characters.md           # optional
        timeline.md             # optional
        chapters/
          ch01.md
        plans/
          ch01_plan.md
        critique/
          ch01_critique.md
        revisions/
          ch01_revision.md
        memory/
          events.md
          relationships.md
          foreshadowing.md
          mistakes.md

system/
  prompts/
    planner.md
    series-plan.md
    writer.md
    writer-cleanup.md
    critic.md
    editor.md
    memory-updater.md
    series-continuity.md
  mistakes/
    planner-mistakes.md
    series-plan-mistakes.md
    writer-mistakes.md
    writer-cleanup-mistakes.md
    critic-mistakes.md
    editor-mistakes.md
    memory-updater-mistakes.md
    series-continuity-mistakes.md
```

## Optional Grouping: World And Universe

Stories may optionally be grouped so they can share canon. Grouping is additive: an ungrouped project under `books/<project_id>/` keeps working exactly as above. A grouped project nests one or two canon containers above the story.

```text
books/
  <universe_id>/                  # universe container (shared cosmology)
    cosmology.md                  # universe-wide canon: origin, physics, philosophy
    characters.md                 # optional: figures that cross worlds
    timeline.md                   # optional: universe meta-timeline
    rules/
      universe.mdc                # optional universe-level rules

    <world_id>/                   # a world inside the universe (shared setting + magic)
      world-rules.md              # world-wide canon: magic system, world physics
      characters.md               # optional: figures shared across this world's stories
      timeline.md                 # optional: world meta-timeline
      rules/
        world.mdc                 # optional world-level rules

      <project_id>/               # a story inside the world: standalone OR series
        rules/
          project.mdc
          style.mdc
        # ...then the standalone or series layout from above, unchanged

# A world may also exist without a universe:
books/
  <world_id>/
    world-rules.md
    <project_id>/ ...
```

### Role Detection

- A folder is a `universe` when it holds universe canon (`cosmology.md` and/or `rules/universe.mdc`) and contains `world` subfolders.
- A folder is a `world` when it holds world canon (`world-rules.md` and/or `rules/world.mdc`) and contains story subfolders.
- A folder is a story when it holds `rules/project.mdc` plus a `standalone` or `series` layout.
- Nesting depth is fixed: `universe -> world -> story`. A story is never nested inside another story.

### Grouping Notes

- Put the broadest shared facts in the highest container that needs them: cosmology at the universe, magic system and world physics at the world, story-specific canon in the story.
- Do not copy shared canon down into each story. Stories reference the world and universe layers instead of duplicating them.
- Each story still keeps its own `outline.md`, `characters.md`, `memory/`, chapters, and (for `series`) `volumes/`.

## Notes

- `books/_template/` is the reusable starter structure for new projects.
- `books/<project_id>/rules/` stores local rules for a specific book or series.
- Local project rules define style and narrative parameters for that project.
- `system/prompts/` stores reusable role prompts for workflow stages.
- `system/mistakes/` stores agent-specific cross-book mistakes, such as `writer-mistakes.md`, which are loaded through the matching prompt.
- `series` projects keep long-range canon at the project root and book-local canon inside `volumes/<book_id>/`.
- `standalone` projects continue to use the simpler single-book layout and do not require `volumes/`.
